column52: For IBD patients: Based from feedback from our participants so far, we have been asked to assess potential areas of importance for future directions of research in IBD wellbeing.  Please choose an...
column53: Any further comments that you feel are important and have not been addressed? (Please do NOT enter any identifiable information e.g. your name, date of birth)

I think it would be important for people to be more aware of how many areas of your life IBD affects.  It is not just a disease that makes you need the toilet a lot.  It affects your mental health, your joints, your energy levels, your skin, your relationships - everything.
My disease is currently quite well controlled with medicine.  But I do worry that could change at any time.

When I was diagnosed at 15 and experienced a moderate flare up, I thought my life was over. I was severely depressed and nobody understood what I was suffering, making a lot of people distance themselves from me. When the doctors put me on the right medication I was able to find the will power to get better and make my life normal again. Now, almost six years later I barely have an issue with it. I keep to a healthy and specific diet that works for me and exercise as often as I can. I don’t have to think about my Crohn’s because it’s not affecting me daily, which really improves my well-being. Thank you for doing this study. I believe that nobody truly understands what I went through and educating people on the reality of it is so important.
I have an ileostomy so this may affect some of the answers

Although I have no bowel symptoms, I have constant fatigue and joint and widespread, pretty severe, joint and muscle pain, which my GP is not interested in and my workplace are totally unsympathetic towards.

When my husband had a minor injury to his finger he received far more sympathy than when I had severe Crohn’s flare. My mental health is definitely worse during a flare up and Crohn’s has affected my enjoyment and ability as a mother to my boy (age 2.5)

Constipation is an issue with IBD which is often overlooked- even by this survey

I have a colostomy which may skew some of the answers. It would be useful to include questions surrounding secondary conditions caused by IBD, I have several which massively impacts my wellbeing- Hidradenitis suppurativa, vulval crohns, axial spondyloarthritis, anaemia. Despite being remission, I have daily struggles and pain due to these issues so remission isnt really an accurate description. Having an effective and approachable IBD team has been a lifeline for me too. Perhaps some open ended questions would give a more reliable account of how IBD effects wellbeing.
N
I have had quite a lot of bowel surgically removed resulting in the loose runny stools all of the time.
It's getting caught outside, no where near a toilet that is the worst. It really is the worst part of this invisible illness and really really annoys and upsets me.

I have had U.C for 11 years. For the first 3 I could say yes all of the time to every question. I would be in the toilet upto 50 times during the day and night. I lost a lot of weight and had frequent 'accidents' I take Azathioprine and Mezavant and have been remission for 8 years. I also am very careful about what I eat.

Just found that I had a resistance to a biologic so another one has just been tried and success was achieved after 48 hours.  Symptoms lessened, so I can now go out!  Steroids helped too, and quick intervention at that, again, improvements seen after 48 hours.  Almost immediate game changer, and that has made an improvement to physical and mental wellbeing.  The past 2 weeks (and previous couple of months) have been challenging, but manageable, with being sensible about the condition, and identifying what works and what does not. I am lucky to be able to work from home, which helps, see clients who have good facilities when I need to do so, and plan the day, travel at sensible times and choose my appointments to the second.  This is so that I manage the condition, rather than it controls me.  This is a big part of my philosophy.  Crack on, have as normal a life as poss, do what you are supposed to do and make the most of it.  There will be difficult days, but the good out way the bad.  This is just a flare, it will pass with the correct management (hopefully).  Timing wasn't great, but hey, when is it?!  Thanks for the opportunity of being part of the research, keep up the good work and crack on!
None
Symptoms of crohns remain even when remission, this seems to be forgotten about and many people act confused by this. They see symptoms as a flare and remission as no symptoms

This prolonged my suffering. The lack of understanding is awful amongst some drs/nurses.

While my condition is remission I do find that I am often tired. I can do all I want but the minute I stop I find it difficult to get going again. I am naturally positive so don’t let my illness get me down but I sometimes worry that I am just ignoring it because I am well. I go to my regular yearly check up and then just get on with life the rest of the time. I was very ill when I was diagnosed but didn’t have time to stop and think about it so just plowed on and didn’t take time to really learn about my illness. I’ve learnt the things that affect me, generally worry/upset rather than food so am aware of that.

I was diagnosed just a few months ago. I take Budenofalk 9 mg daily and Pentasa 3 mg. I do not have other symptoms than barely noticeable sharp pain on my lower right side of the belly, so generally I feel good. However, my diagnosis was frightening, but with the help of my psychologist I mostly overcame the fear. I still worry at times about disease progression and whether I can get adequate treatment to live a healthy, active and happy life. I find hope in the fact that I can participate in such type of research and be active in the advancement of knowledge and treatments for IBD. Also, I mentioned that I live outside the UK, but I do spend quite a lot of time in England.

This is not necessarily the case for a colostomy or a none-ostomate.

column53: I have had to stop my maintenance regime…adalimumab and azathioprine, due to serious infection and 5 week hospital stay. It took 3 years to get into remission an drink the right drug regime that worked.  I am now starting over again with new medication.  It is the worry that it could take a long time to get back to remission and find a engine that works for me,  this is what puts my life on hold and makes me feel anxious and frustrated.  Life at times can feel it’s ruled by hospital appointments, regular blood tests, ordering and collecting monthly prescriptions from gp, being in to  take regular delivery of cold/fridge    medications. It really does feel like your life is ruled by the treatment. As I no longer work, my anticipated life of freedom and get up and go away whenever I want really isn’t a possibility.  My diary is full of dates where my medication rules the roost. This, at times seems worse than the IBD.

column53: My baby is 10 months old & doesn’t sleep well. He still woke 5/6 times a night until about a month ago, it’s better now but he still wakes about 3 times a night.  I’m on Octasa and in the process of reducing from the treatment dose (6 tablets a day) after being on it for 18 months. Currently taking 4 tablets a day and worrying that the recent bowel symptoms eg wind / more bowel movements may be the start of a flare… I’m also in the process of weaning my baby into formula ready to return to work which is difficult emotionally and physically. I’m also waiting for treatment from the perinatal mental health team - was referred when my baby was 2 months old, assessed 2 months ago (8 months old) but warned I’ve got a long wait for treatment - I’ve been told I should begin treatment before my baby’s 2 years old but if not I’ll be discharged from the perinatal service and join the back of the ‘regular’ mental health support queue. This is despite experiencing what my assessor describes as “severe psychological distress”. I worry that my poor mental health will cause my IBD to flare again but feel powerless to help myself / get help.

column53: People still assume IBD is "just a bit of tummy trouble" it's still not really seen as a disability by most people/companies. column53: Frustration comes from IBD set up. Call IBD team when ill/need advice, answering machine says extremely busy, call back may be up to 5 days. Secretary calls back with appointment to speak to nurse. Six different nurses means having to explain everything again. No overview, no consistency. Answer machine also says if urgent call GP or 111. I speak to GP who says I need to speak to IBD team. IBD nurses don’t always seem to fully listen or understand my Crohn’s which seems atypical. Do not always feel listened to and feel decisions lead to unnecessary and often detrimental delays.

column53: I developed bile acid malabsorbtion after bowel surgery.  This has left me with episodes of incontinence. I didn't even know this condition existed before I developed it. If I'd have known it was a possible side effect of surgery,  and it was explained properly, I honestly would have refused surgery. I was made medically redundant in 2022 due to my crohns disease and associated symptoms and I doubt I'll be able to return back to work again. Which as a person in my 30s is really hard. I waited a year for long term health condition counselling to help me stay in work,  lost my job before I've even reached the top of the waiting list.  There is such little help.

column53:
I have had Crohn’s for 15 years now but have also suffered with AS - Ankylosing Spondylitis at the same time as both are chronic and possibly connected it would be really helpful if I could have an appointment with my clinicians at the same time !! Or that they would confer together about both my diseases , I’m used to it now but in the early days the treatment plans have clashed once on biologicals it has become easier as the drug covers both but it is complicated and as I’m ageing both of my diseases are changing !! 

Also even though my diseases are remission most of the time it has still required me to completely change my lifestyle mostly because of the effects of fatigue !! I am just not able to do all the things I want to achieve but more importantly I have to say NO to many things and people just have no perception of quite how exhausting the diseases are and because I take a biological they assume I’m cured / on top form !!! Without realising the effort involved in coping with side effects 

 I am most definitely now able to live a full and happy life on biologicals but it takes a lot of planning and is an all day daily task !!

I have elderly parents , children with partners , young grandchildren , a sister having breast cancer treatment and a husband and like everyone else it’s a busy life and they all need me but I also have two chronic illnesses which if they had their way would have me bedridden and permanently on a toilet !!! 
Society and life don’t give you a break and it’s learning the way to cope with it all and manage that’s key so anything you can do to help us to do that would be wonderful .

My I just say Thankyou !! Knowing that people care and are trying to make a difference for us is super encouraging!!

column53: Many of my problems are as a result of multiple surgeries and I feel that this is an area that is not considered in research or in clinic. Even though I am technically remission I have many complicated symptoms as a result of a hemicolectomy in 1989 carried out as an emergency and then a resection in 2014. My issues often feel dismissed by clinicians and the wider IBD community. This gets very tiring and my quality of life has been significantly affected since the second surgery. I have not been over seas on holiday for 8 years or eaten out. My diet is so restricted I can sometimes struggle to work a full day away from home. This has restricted my career opportunities and lifestyle overall. Further research addressing pthe needs of patients who have had multiple surgeries would be great.

column52: Fatigue;Diet and alcohol;Menstruation;Stress;Pain;Mental health ;Education and support after diagnosis ;Relationships and intimacy ;Menopause;Medical trauma. Coping with medication side effects and invasive medical procedures and hospital admissions. Coping with constipation alongside bowel problems and how confusing that is. Eating disorders in IBD. ;
column53:
Having your body constantly invaded with procedures or aggressive medications is very distressing and the impact of this is often overlooked. I have been diagnosed with medical trauma ptsd as a result of all my ongoing medical interventions.

Managing healthcare becomes all consuming and a full time job and there is no support for this side of it 

Also it’s important to ask IBD patients if they have other illnesses.. when there are comorbidities things get very challenging.. medications get even more confusing and capacity to focus on healing IBD gets very hard as it’s hard to manage everything all at once.. mobility problems due to physical injuries mean IBD is much harder to manage and so on.

column53:
As someone with IBD I am more prone to infections. From 2019-2020 I had recurring bladder infections and I now think I have chronic bladder problems - I wake up several times a night to empty my bladder yet it never feels like it is fully emptied, and needing to empty my bowels also increases the symptoms of needing to empty my bladder as well. Is there any correlation between bowel and bladder issues, e.g. is it normal/common to have issues with both? 

I’d also be interested to understand what it really means to be “remission” - since starting imraldi my bowel symptoms have become significantly more manageable, but at the same time I am always completely exhausted and am always unwell. It seems like managing IBD is more complicated than simply getting my bowel symptoms under control, but I don’t know what else to do to improve my quality of life.

column52: Fatigue;Stress;Pain;IBD occurs often with SIBO and IBS, but most doctors have no idea what to do with IBS aside from diagnose you with it. I and others I've talked to honestly want research mainly directed at finding better treatments / a cure for IBD & SIBO / IBS, since wellbeing and mental health problems stem from those diseases, but if there has to be research on ancillary things like well-being then it should focus on educating doctors, and also making prescriptions for medications like Rifaximin more accessible and cheaper. ;
column53:
Same as above, so I'll just copy/paste:

IBD occurs often with SIBO and IBS, but most doctors have no idea what to do with IBS aside from diagnose you with it. I and others I've talked to honestly want research mainly directed at finding better treatments / a cure for IBD & SIBO / IBS, since wellbeing and mental health problems stem from those diseases, but if there has to be research on ancillary things like well-being then it should focus on educating doctors, and also making prescriptions for medications like Rifaximin more accessible and cheaper. 

*Also, on #23 - "On how many days in the last two weeks, have you felt off your food?" I wasn't sure what it meant by "off your food" so I just guessed it meant how many days haven't you eaten a regular diet.

Thanks for your work on IBD!

column53: I was diagnosed during COVID. I was so confused as I was informed I had uc. Another professional mentioned proctitis, another professional spoke about possibly having IBS or food intolerance. I’ve struggled with inconsistent consultations and advice during 2 flare ups. I’m feel a bit lost with it all sometimes and usually end up waiting until I’m really struggling with blood/mucus/fatigue before seeking advice. I understand I am not nearly affected as some people but I do feel isolated as I don’t know anyone else who has collitis so it can be difficult explaining how unwell I feel with a condition that’s not visible. I finished steroids around 5 weeks ago and I am starting to see mucus again but feel Im not unwell enough yet to make contact with the IBD team as they probably deal with really ill people needing support and at the moment, I’m doing ok.

column53: the pain and pressure I feel in my back regularly related to bowel blockages is one of the hardest symptoms to deal with as the pain level is out of control and really affects my life. it's something that is difficult to find information on and barely mentioned. I also believe my sphincter and bowel muscles have been impacted so much by this disease that they no longer work as they should which causes me massive issues and most of the time I can only make a bowel movement if digitally encouraged. The spasms of pain and pressure in this area feels like early labour.
